<h3>Software and Lab Information</h3>
<ul>
	<li>This course is divided into four blocks, corresponding to the four tests.  In general the pattern will be that a unit will be covered in lecture and the following class period will be devoted to working in the lab.</li>
	<li>The course is based on the version of SQL implemented by Microsoft Access.  Microsoft Access is installed in the computer science department lab, <a href='https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Social+Sciences+Building,+Alumni+Drive,+Anchorage,+AK&amp;hl=en&amp;ll=61.190573,-149.819645&amp;spn=0.002745,0.009645&amp;sll=61.108864,-149.440311&amp;sspn=0.704636,2.469177&amp;oq=Social+Science&amp;hnear=Social+Sciences+Bldg,+3190+Alumni+Dr,+Anchorage,+Alaska+99508&amp;t=m&amp;z=17'>SSB 172</a>. You can get into that lab using your student id. Microsoft Access is also available in the university&rsquo;s <a href='http://www.uaa.alaska.edu/computerlabs/anchoragecampus/'>ITS Open Computer Labs</a>.</li>
	<li>If you have a personal computer of your own, it may have Microsoft Access installed on it or you may be able to acquire a copy.  Note that it doesn't have to be the latest version.  The example database will work with versions of Access as old as Access 2000.  If you choose to use an older version, you would have to deal with differences in the user interface and minor changes in the implementation of SQL.</li>
	<li>If you want to use an alternative to Microsoft Office there are many options. Another open source project called LibreOffice provides similar functionality to the Office collection. The database program in the suite is known as Base.  You can download this program and get more information at <a href='http://www.libreoffice.org'>www.libreoffice.org</a>. Other implementations of SQL may also be used such as MySQL, Sqlite, and Microsoft SQL Server.</li>
	<li>What you have to keep in mind is that there are likely to be inconsistencies between Microsoft Access and the other implementations of SQL. If you choose to work with Base, you will have to deal with the fact that the course materials are oriented towards Microsoft Access. I will accept assignments in any of these formats.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id='applications'>Supported Applications</h3>
<p>Multiple SQL products are supported in this class. As a result you may choose which application to design your queries in. Feel free to choose from the below list a SQL database type that will work well for you. All products are free for personal use.</p>
<ul>
	<li>
		<p><strong>SQLite</strong> - A lightweight SQL database stored in a file. Very easy to install but lacking in usability.</p>
		<p><a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/sqlite-manager/">SQLite Manager Firefox Extension</a></p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p><strong>MySQL</strong> - Full-fledged database server. Some implementations may deeply integrate with your system. I have provided some suggestions that keep that to a minimum. Note that MySQL requires a separate product to work with the databases.</p>
		<p>
			Servers: <a href='http://www.apachefriends.org/en/xampp.html'>XAMPP</a>, <a href='http://www.mamp.info/en/index.html'>MAMP (Mac)</a>, <a href='http://www.wampserver.com/en/'>WAMP (Win)</a><br/>
			Clients: <a href='http://www.sequelpro.com/'>Sequel Pro (Mac)</a>, <a href='http://www.heidisql.com/'>HeidiSQL (Win)</a>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<p><strong>Microsoft SQL Server</strong> - Another full database server. This is Windows-only and is a rather large installation, however the product comes with its own management studio for working with SQL.</p>
		<p><a href='http://www.microsoft.com/sqlserver/en/us/editions/2012-editions/express.aspx'>Microsoft SQL Server Express</a></p>
	</li>
</ul>

<h3>Assignments</h3>
<ul>
	<li>BlackBoard is not used for this course other than the syllabus and course evaluations.</li>
	<li>The assignments are posted on the course Web page.</li>
	<li>Each unit has a set of numbered questions.  What you have to turn in for credit are the answers to any 5 questions for each unit.</li>
	<li>I am flexible with how you turn in your assignments. If you would like to number each answer in the layout of the assignment sheet that is acceptable. You may also turn in a .sql file containing your queries, but make sure that each query is prefixed with a comment describing which question it pertains to. Turning in the result set for a query will not be enough.</li>
	<li>It is in your interest to do at the very least either all of the evens, or all of the odds for each assignment.  This will give you comprehensive practice on what will be covered on tests.</li>
	<li>You turn in your assignments by email to my email address: <a href='mailto:srnixon@uaa.alaska.edu'>srnixon@uaa.alaska.edu</a>.</li>
	<li>The database for each assignments will be posted on assignment's specific Web page. In order to complete your assignment you will have to open this database and run your queries against it.</li>
	<li>Any version of Access later than the 2000 version should be able to open this database.</li>
	<li>It makes sense to save up all of the units belonging to a given test and send me queries for the assignments up through that test. The assignments for the units covered by a given test are due in my email box before the class period when the test is given.</li>
	<li>When applicable, I will post result sets for each question of an assignment that you can compare your results to. If you have questions you can ask me in person or send me email.</li>
	<li>How you do your homework is up to you.  More than one student may work together, for example, but all students have to hand in their own copies of the assignments in order to get individual credit. Under this system it would be possible for you to copy and paste the posted answers into your copy of the database, or exchange answers with other students in electronic form.  Let your conscience be your guide.</li>
	<li>The majority of points in the course come from tests, so test scores will have the greatest effect on the grade you receive. This does not mean that you can skip the assignments and only work on the tests. The assignments will have a cumulative effect on both your points as well as your knowledge of the test material. I highly suggest completing your assignments early and reviewing those answers before a test.</li>
</ul>

