<h3>Tests</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Tests will consist of questions asking you to write SQL queries, as well as short answer questions.  Tests will be done with paper and pencil, not on the computer.</li>
	<li>The number of tests and their dates will not be changed.  If, by chance, less material is covered than is shown in the timeline before a test, only the material covered will be included on the test.</li>
	<li>Tests will be scheduled for a full class period and they will be given in the room where lectures are given, not in the lab.  It is up to you to pay attention to the syllabus and make sure you're going to the right room on any given day, especially a test day.</li>
	<li>There will not be a formal review for tests. If students come the day before the test with questions, as much of that period as is needed will be taken up answering them.  If students don't come with questions, the time will be devoted to other things.</li>
	<li>Using any resources not specifically approved by the instructor in advance when taking a test will result in a score reduced, possibly to zero.  These "forbidden" resources can be of any kind, including, but not limited to, consulting with someone else while taking the test, written notes, computer or other media, etc.</li>
	<li>If a student cannot take a test at the regularly scheduled time, a request to take it at an alternative time should be made in advance.  I try to have tests graded and hand them back one week after the day of the test. The last possible time to make up a test is the class period when it is being handed back corrected. In cases of emergency, when it&rsquo;s not possible to make a request in advance, requests will be considered up until the next class period.  It is not possible to make up a test after I have handed back graded copies.</li>
	<li>Note this carefully:  10 points will be deducted from the score on any test that is taken after the scheduled time.  Some people need to take tests late because of unforeseen emergencies, others need to because they have too many tests scheduled on one day, etc.  It is not possible for me to decide which cases are more worthy than others.  10 points will simply come off the top of any test which is not in my possession at the end of the scheduled test period.  10 points on one test is not likely to make the difference between one letter grade and another at the end of the semester.  If it happens more than once, it could have an effect.</li>
	<li>The 3 midterms and the final count equally.  The final test is not cumulative.  It is simply another test like the midterms, covering the material since the last midterm.  At the end of the semester the lowest individual test score will be thrown out and the total number of points earned in the course will be calculated on the basis of the 3 remaining test scores plus the points earned for homework.  In a situation where a student has not been able to take a test before I hand it back corrected, the student will have to take a zero on the test and rely on this policy to throw the score out.</li>
</ul>

